Dire Straits’ "Sultans of Swing: The Very Best of Dire Straits" is strong in other ways — pristine mixes, melodic songwriting, intimate Knopfler vocals and thoughtful sequencing that reward front‑to‑back listening — and it aligns with my secondary interest in songwriter‑driven records with layered arrangements and emotional clarity. However, compared to the Monkees set it is less of the immediate, hook‑first, singalong compilation I emphasized. Dire Straits’ strengths are more album‑oriented dynamics and subtle storytelling rather than the short, instantly gratifying pop singles and bold vocal harmonies that I foreground. Because I explicitly prefer tight greatest‑hits style sequencing and instant melodic payoff (and dislike sequencing or album forms that demand long uninterrupted plays to be rewarding), the Monkees compilation is the closer match.
In short: the Monkees CD checks nearly every item on my primary checklist — concise, hooky singles; theatrical/close vocal presentation and harmonies; punchy, attentive mastering; and a greatest‑hits sequencing that delivers immediate payoff — so I choose the Monkees greatest‑hits and reject the Dire Straits compilation despite its high quality, because Dire Straits leans more toward album‑oriented, subtler songwriting that doesn’t fit my stated preference for instant, singalong hits.

