- Vocals and harmonies: Déjà Vu describes “tight three‑/four‑part vocal stacks that breathe,” which implies controlled doubling and harmonies that sit naturally without smothering the lead — exactly the balance I favor (layered harmonies that thicken choruses without burying the lead). Candidate 2, while offering “tactile breathy midrange lead vocals” and “lush multitracked harmonies,” raises two concerns relative to my dislikes: (1) “breathy midrange lead vocals” can reduce intelligibility and presence compared with the dry, close‑miked lead I prefer; (2) “lush multitracked harmonies” can cross the line into burying the lead or creating a homogenized midrange unless explicitly controlled. Déjà Vu’s description more clearly promises intelligible leads and well‑controlled stacks.
- Separation, imaging, and tonal character: Déjà Vu highlights “crystalline separation and wide imaging” plus “vintage tape sheen,” matching my desire for analogue warmth, wide stereo imaging and good instrument separation that rewards front‑to‑back listening. Candidate 2 also offers warm tape sheen and wide imaging, but combined with the breathy midrange vocal descriptor it suggests a mix that emphasizes midrange warmth over the clear, presence‑forward vocal and percussion snap I prize.
- Avoidance of disliked attributes: Déjà Vu expressly avoids “heavy compression or synth‑first gloss” and preserves transients — this directly counters the mid‑focused arena sheen, heavy limiting and over‑processing I dislike. Candidate 2 does promise low compression, but the “breathy” lead and “lush” harmonies present a greater risk of reduced vocal immediacy or a more homogenized midrange.
Conclusion and rejection of the other CD:
- I choose Warm 1970 Déjà Vu because its combination of restrained, unembellished mastering, preserved transients and headroom, acoustic/guitar focus with expressive solos, tight but breathing vocal stacks, and crystalline separation aligns most closely and explicitly with my stated priorities (snap, analogue warmth, presence‑forward intelligible vocals, and separation).
- I reject the Piano‑centered early‑70s double LP because, although it shares desirable traits (warm tape sheen, preserved headroom, tactile piano transients and wide imaging), its “breathy midrange lead vocals” and “lush multitracked harmonies” risk reduced vocal immediacy and potential midrange masking—exactly the aspects I said I dislike—making it the less suitable match.

