- Dislikes: mid‑focused, arena‑sheen remasters that soften percussive attack or reduce vocal immediacy; thin/over‑processed sheen; heavy limiting or loudness that flattens micro‑dynamics; production that buries vocals or creates a homogenized midrange; distant, overly restrained vocal stacks.
2) Evaluation of the two candidates against those points
- CD 2 (Pristinely remastered, presence‑forward vocals): Matches many of my core preferences directly — presence‑forward, close‑miked dry lead vocals (exactly the vocal immediacy I prize); analogue warmth and preserved transient snap (keeps the tactile attack and micro‑dynamics I want); modest compression and low limiting (maintains headroom and avoids flattening dynamics); tactile keys and punchy bass/drums called out; clear layered harmonies that do not appear to bury the lead; full‑length solos and front‑to‑back, detail‑rich listening. Overall it directly addresses nearly every stated preference and avoids the specific dislikes (no mid‑smothering arena sheen, no heavy limiting, no buried vocals).
- CD 1 (Mid‑focused, tape‑rich arena AOR remaster): Has several strengths that I like — preserved transient attack, punchy gated drums, tight bass, low compression, generous headroom, roomy stereo and intact solos. However, it is explicitly described as mid‑focused with “massive multitracked crunchy guitars and stacked vocal harmonies up front” and an “arena AOR” character. That mid‑focus and upfront stacked harmonies risk producing the arena‑sheen and homogenized midrange I said I dislike, and they can reduce lead vocal immediacy or bury a dry, close lead. Even though percussive attack and headroom are preserved, the emphasis on multitracked guitars and harmonies “up front” conflicts with my priority for a presence‑forward, intelligible dry lead and clear instrument separation.
3) Decision rationale
I select CD 2 because it aligns far more completely with my listening priorities: it explicitly delivers presence‑forward, close‑miked dry lead vocals, analogue warmth, preserved transient snap, modest compression/low limiting (so micro‑dynamics and headroom are maintained), tactile keys and punchy bass/drums, and clear layered harmonies that don’t overwhelm the lead. Those attributes map directly to the central items in my preference set.
I reject CD 1 despite some technical positives (good transients, punchy drums, headroom and intact solos) because its mid‑focused, arena AOR presentation with massive multitracked guitars and stacked harmonies up front matches the very remastering traits I said I dislike: a mid‑dominated sheen that can homogenize the midrange and reduce lead vocal immediacy. In short, CD 1 trades some clarity of lead vocal presence and separation for an arena, mid‑forward sound that runs counter to my stated priorities, whereas CD 2 preserves vocal immediacy, dynamics, and instrument separation — exactly what I prize.

